




TY  - JOUR
T1  - Sanctions
AU  - Eaton, Jonathan
AU  - Engers, Maxim
Y1  - 1992/10/01
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261845
DO  - 10.1086/261845
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 899
EP  - 928
VL  - 100
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Sanctions are measures that one party (the sender) uses to influence another (the target). Sanctions, or the threat of sanctions, have been used by governments to alter the human rights, trade, or foreign policies of other governments. We develop notions of the sender's and target's toughness that depend on their patience and on the extent of their suffering from sanctions. How much a sender can exact from the target depends on the relative toughness of the two. Sanctions that impose less harm on the target can sometimes be more effective than those that impose greater harm.
AB  - Sanctions are measures that one party (the sender) uses to influence another (the target). Sanctions, or the threat of sanctions, have been used by governments to alter the human rights, trade, or foreign policies of other governments. We develop notions of the sender's and target's toughness that depend on their patience and on the extent of their suffering from sanctions. How much a sender can exact from the target depends on the relative toughness of the two. Sanctions that impose less harm on the target can sometimes be more effective than those that impose greater harm.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261845
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261845
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Competition in the British Electricity Spot Market
AU  - Green, Richard J.
AU  - Newbery, David M.
Y1  - 1992/10/01
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261846
DO  - 10.1086/261846
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 929
EP  - 953
VL  - 100
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Most of the British electricity supply industry has been privatized. Two dominant generators supply bulk electricity to an unregulated "pool." They submit a supply schedule of prices for generation and receive the market-clearing price, which varies with demand. Despite claims that this should be highly competitive, we show that the Nash equilibrium in supply schedules implies a high markup on marginal cost and substantial deadweight losses. Further simulations, to show the effect of entry by 1994, produce somewhat lower prices, at the cost of excessive entry; subdividing the generators into five firms would produce better results.
AB  - Most of the British electricity supply industry has been privatized. Two dominant generators supply bulk electricity to an unregulated "pool." They submit a supply schedule of prices for generation and receive the market-clearing price, which varies with demand. Despite claims that this should be highly competitive, we show that the Nash equilibrium in supply schedules implies a high markup on marginal cost and substantial deadweight losses. Further simulations, to show the effect of entry by 1994, produce somewhat lower prices, at the cost of excessive entry; subdividing the generators into five firms would produce better results.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261846
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261846
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Price Discrimination in Competitive Markets
AU  - Locay, Luis
AU  - Rodriguez, Alvaro
Y1  - 1992/10/01
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261847
DO  - 10.1086/261847
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 954
EP  - 965
VL  - 100
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We present models in which price discrimination in the context of a two-part price can occur in some competitive markets. Purchases take place in groups, which choose which firms to patronize. While firms are perfectly competitive with respect to groups, they have some market power over individual consumers, who are constrained by their groups' choices. We find that firms will charge an entry fee that is below marginal cost, and the second part of the price is marked up above marginal cost. The markup not only is positive but increases with the quality of the product.
AB  - We present models in which price discrimination in the context of a two-part price can occur in some competitive markets. Purchases take place in groups, which choose which firms to patronize. While firms are perfectly competitive with respect to groups, they have some market power over individual consumers, who are constrained by their groups' choices. We find that firms will charge an entry fee that is below marginal cost, and the second part of the price is marked up above marginal cost. The markup not only is positive but increases with the quality of the product.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261847
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261847
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Measuring Peer Group Effects: A Study of Teenage Behavior
AU  - Evans, William N.
AU  - Oates, Wallace E.
AU  - Schwab, Robert M.
Y1  - 1992/10/01
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261848
DO  - 10.1086/261848
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 966
EP  - 991
VL  - 100
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Individuals or households often have some scope for choice of peer groups, whether through the selection of neighborhood of residence, school, or friends. This study addresses the estimation of peer group effects in cases in which measures of peer group influence are potentially endogenous variables. Using a rich data set on individual behavior, the paper explores teenage pregnancy and school dropout behavior. For both cases, the estimation of a straight-forward single-equation model yields statistically significant peer group effects; however, these effects disappear under simultaneous equation estimation. The results are robust and suggest the need for careful modeling of the choice of peer groups.
AB  - Individuals or households often have some scope for choice of peer groups, whether through the selection of neighborhood of residence, school, or friends. This study addresses the estimation of peer group effects in cases in which measures of peer group influence are potentially endogenous variables. Using a rich data set on individual behavior, the paper explores teenage pregnancy and school dropout behavior. For both cases, the estimation of a straight-forward single-equation model yields statistically significant peer group effects; however, these effects disappear under simultaneous equation estimation. The results are robust and suggest the need for careful modeling of the choice of peer groups.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261848
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261848
Y2  - 2024/03/22
